  "@Quentin-M: @adnankobir Could you describe how does bind-tools help exactly? The package [only include](https://pkgs.alpinelinux.org/contents?branch=edge&name=bind-tools&arch=x86&repo=main) binaries such as dig, nslookup, while the issue is present at the kernel level, triggered by libc's behavior on lookups, itself triggered by applications' code directly. Were those binaries triggering the bug themselves, and now does not anymore? \r\n\r\nI have however developed last week a [workaround](https://github.com/weaveworks/weave/issues/3287#issuecomment-390383565) based on the use of [tc](http://man7.org/linux/man-pages/man8/tc.8.html), that can be deployed cluster-scope with just a few lines, and that fixes the issue across the board without having to do any kind of pod hack.",
  "@KIVagant: FYI: `single-request-reopen` didn't help in my case (https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/56903#issuecomment-359897058)\r\n\r\nKubernetes 1.10, AWS\r\n\r\n```\r\n# cat /etc/resolv.conf\r\nnameserver 100.64.0.10\r\nsearch default.svc.cluster.local svc.cluster.local cluster.local ec2.internal\r\noptions ndots:5\r\noptions single-request-reopen\r\n```\r\n\r\n```\r\nCaused by: io.netty.resolver.dns.DnsNameResolverTimeoutException: [/100.64.0.10:53] query timed out after 5000 milliseconds (no stack trace available)\r\n```\r\nOS in container:\r\n```\r\nPRETTY_NAME=\"Debian GNU/Linux 9 (stretch)\"\r\nNAME=\"Debian GNU/Linux\"\r\nVERSION_ID=\"9\"\r\nVERSION=\"9 (stretch)\"\r\n```\r\n\r\nI don't know if Netty or OpenJDK support this option",
  "@Quentin-M: @KIVagant \r\n\r\nThis is a libc option, this does not generally depend on the application but on the libc used. Except if they have their own implementation of the resolv stack (which I don't know for OpenJDK/Netty)\r\n\r\nPlease however confirm that the issue actually comes from the conntrack race condition we are talking about, or something else. To confirm, use `watch -n1 conntrack -S` and check whether the `insert_failed` column is increasing as you are getting time-outs.\r\n\r\nMy tc-based workaround should fix your issue if that's the case.",
  "@KIVagant: @Quentin-M , I've been waiting for a while and now can say that `insert_failed` column is not increasing when I'm getting new DNS errors in the application log.\r\n\r\n```\r\n$ kubectl logs my-service-5466c54fdf-g2vfb | grep \"failed to resolve\" | wc -l\r\n22\r\n$ kubectl exec -it my-service-5466c54fdf-g2vfb -- conntrack -S\r\nentries   \t\t90\r\nsearched  \t\t2228\r\nfound     \t\t3774748\r\nnew       \t\t132421\r\ninvalid   \t\t1\r\nignore    \t\t0\r\ndelete    \t\t327481\r\ndelete_list\t\t327481\r\ninsert    \t\t132421\r\ninsert_failed\t\t0\r\ndrop      \t\t0\r\nearly_drop\t\t0\r\nicmp_error\t\t0\r\nexpect_new\t\t0\r\nexpect_create\t\t0\r\nexpect_delete\t\t0\r\nsearch_restart\t\t0\r\nconntrack v1.4.4 (conntrack-tools): Operation failed: sorry, you must be root or get CAP_NET_ADMIN capability to do this\r\ncommand terminated with exit code 1\r\n```",
  "@Quentin-M: @KIVagant What about on the hosts themselves (conntrack -S)?",
  "@KIVagant: ```\r\nkubectl get node |grep -v NAME |  awk '{print $1}' | xargs -i sh -c 'ssh admin@{} -- hostname -f; sudo conntrack -S'\r\n\r\nip-10-111-115-29.ec2.internal\r\ncpu=0   \tsearched=209446 found=39800914 new=1831916 invalid=2889 ignore=7053695 delete=1831782 delete_list=1831782 insert=1831916 insert_failed=0 drop=0 early_drop=0 error=102 search_restart=0\r\ncpu=1   \tsearched=0 found=0 new=0 invalid=0 ignore=0 delete=0 delete_list=0 insert=0 insert_failed=0 drop=0 early_drop=0 error=0 search_restart=0\r\ncpu=2   \tsearched=0 found=0 new=0 invalid=0 ignore=0 delete=0 delete_list=0 insert=0 insert_failed=0 drop=0 early_drop=0 error=0 search_restart=0\r\ncpu=3   \tsearched=0 found=0 new=0 invalid=0 ignore=0 delete=0 delete_list=0 insert=0 insert_failed=0 drop=0 early_drop=0 error=0 search_restart=0\r\ncpu=4   \tsearched=0 found=0 new=0 invalid=0 ignore=0 delete=0 delete_list=0 insert=0 insert_failed=0 drop=0 early_drop=0 error=0 search_restart=0\r\ncpu=5   \tsearched=0 found=0 new=0 invalid=0 ignore=0 delete=0  [trimmed]",
  "@Quentin-M: So unfortunately it does seem that the issue you are having is different\nthan the one experienced by various folks here, and that is related to a\nconntrack race,\n",
  "@codebreach: We are also facing this GKE and is making the everything unusable.\r\nThe CloudSQL proxy sidecar fails with i/o timeouts on DNS. Making all app serving pods enter a crash loop.\r\n\r\nI have verified that I can access using ClusterIP but not using DNS.\r\n\r\nIs there a workaround for GKE-Container OS users?",
  "@bboreham: Just joining some dots:\r\nhttps://github.com/weaveworks/weave/issues/3287\r\nhttps://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/issues/45976\r\n\r\nand while I'm talking about dots let me recommend using fully-qualified names where possible, e.g. `google.com.` - the dot at the end stops the resolver from following the search path, so you don't get lookups for `google.com.svc.cluster.local.` and so on.",
  "@Quentin-M: I just posted a little write-up about our journey troubleshooting the issue, and how we are worked around it in production: https://blog.quentin-machu.fr/2018/06/24/5-15s-dns-lookups-on-kubernetes/.",
  "@maxlaverse: Thanks for sharing this @Quentin-M.\r\n\r\n> This means that adding --random-fully does fix the packet loss, as the flag only acts on the SNAT race!\r\n\r\nI believe there is a typo here and you meant **does not** fix the packet loss.\r\n\r\nI'll use this opportunity to clarify one point ;)\r\n\r\nI hope the article about [connection timeouts on Kubernetes](https://tech.xing.com/a-reason-for-unexplained-connection-timeouts-on-kubernetes-docker-abd041cf7e02) was not misleading but this flag `NF_NAT_RANGE_PROTO_RANDOM_FULLY` (or its user-space switch equivalent `--random-fully`) **is not supposed to fix anything** at all.  It allows starting from a random number when incrementally looking for a free port available for a network translation. It mitigates the issue but doesn't solve it. The conntrack record is still created as one of the first hook of the `POSTROUTING` chain and inserted in the conntrack table at one of the last, leading to a race condition.\r\n\r\nI have one question that I think was asked a [trimmed]",
  "@Quentin-M: @maxlaverse Thank you for your note about the typo, for the word usage of \"fix\" that I replaced with \"mitigate\", and for your great initial troubleshooting work!\r\n\r\n> You've tested the ipvs back-end of kube-proxy and it didn't solve the issue.\r\n\r\nThis is what we use daily, yes.\r\n\r\n> The lvs wiki states that the ipvs module uses its own connection tracking system. Since there is only network adress translation to be done, and no filtering or other kind of mangling involved, I had good hope it would work better. Do you know why ?\r\n\r\nThis is is great find, I was not aware at all. Given the wording of the documentation you provided, it would sound like one needs to unload the netfilter conntrack module explicitly to avoid double-tracking, which we haven't done. The information provided in the [kubernetes documentation regarding ipvs](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/tree/master/pkg/proxy/ipvs) is actually confusing, as it states the nf_conntrack_ipv4 must be loaded.\r\n",
  "@mikksoone: Thanks for all the nice writeups regarding S(D)NAT races.\r\n\r\nI (OP) did some testing, and in my case, it's not the race, but something else is throttling DNS. Switching from alpine to ubuntu + options single-request-reopen, made the slow requests even slower. So I decided to see if there are periods when DNS is slow - and indeed, using 8 pods to see when they encounter the slow DNS, this is the chart that came out:\r\n[image]\r\n\r\n\r\nBasically if DNS is slow, then it's slow for many pods at the same time, and might be slow for many consecutive requests. Just to work OK for the next half an hour for everyone.\r\n\r\nThe cluster itself is idling (many cluster in different VPC-s all have the same problem), kube-dns is not being CPU throttled, kube-dns charts look steady without pikes, no errors in kube-dns (or dnsmasq, sidecar) logs and there are no conntrack errors appearing. Hitting AWS DNS QP [trimmed]",
  "@dcowden: wow @mikksoone that is awesome work!  That's definitely an unquestionably regular pattern!  ",
  "@maxlaverse: > this is the chart that came out\r\n\r\nThe Y axis is the number of slow lookups ? After how much time is a lookup considered to be slow ?\r\n\r\n> kube-dns is not being CPU throttled\r\n\r\nJust to rule throttling out, you know this because you haven't set any CPU limit or you could see that `/sys/fs/cgroup/cpu/kubepods/.../nr_throttled = 0` (or equivalent) ?\r\n\r\n> My plan is now to understand if the problem is between pod and kube-dns or between kube-dns and external dns\r\n\r\nWe run tiny Go program as DaemonSet querying CoreDNS (10.96.0.10) (previously kube-dns) and the upstream DNS every few seconds, to monitor the response time and eventually timeouts. You could maybe try something similar ? Is has proven to be really useful to us.\r\n\r\nIs the nameserver configurable in the 8 testing Pods you have ? Could you add a second deployment of those Pods with a different value for it, or change your Spec for `dnsPolicy: None` and a custom `dnsConfig` field ? (never tried it)\r\n\r\nIf you migrate to CoreDNS,  [trimmed]",
  "@mikksoone: > The Y axis is the number of slow lookups ? After how much time is a lookup considered to be slow ?\r\n\r\nSorry for the missing axes, updated the chart. Y is duration in seconds, x is the datetime of request in seconds since epoch. It's considered slow if the request takes more than a second.\r\n\r\n> Just to rule throttling out, you know this because you haven't set any CPU limit or you could see that /sys/fs/cgroup/cpu/kubepods/.../nr_throttled = 0 (or equivalent) ?\r\n\r\nHaven't checked nr_thottled = 0, will do now, but because I see there is no limit, the request is set to 100 + 150 + 10 and prometheus is reporting < 30+30+2 for peaks. (kube-dns+dnsmasq+sidecar)\r\n\r\n> We run tiny Go program as DaemonSet querying CoreDNS (10.96.0.10) (previously kube-dns) and the upstream DNS every few seconds, to monitor the response time and eventually timeouts. You could maybe try something similar ? Is has proven to be really useful to us.\r\n\r\nNice idea, will consider adding this to the monitoring solution [trimmed]",
  "@maxlaverse: > Haven't checked nr_thottled = 0, will do now, but because I see there is no limit, the request is set to 100 + 150 + 10 and prometheus is reporting < 30+30+2 for peaks. (kube-dns+dnsmasq+sidecar)\r\n\r\nNo need to check `nr_thottled` then. If no limit is set it should be 0, or the key is probably not even there\r\n\r\n> It's 1.9 so yes, I can try with \"None\", but I don't have a good idea what configurations to test. With \"default\" it works well, no timeouts ever.\r\n\r\nThe value \"default\" is also fine, that's why I wanted to know, by-passing the in-cluster DNS\r\n\r\n> It's not that weird if you consider the underlying VPC is configured in the same way, kops is used to create cluster in the same way. There are multiple clusters in a very similar environment (think dev vs staging vs prod).\r\n\r\ntrue",
